ltered as a result of association with the common placename ending <i>-well</i> ‘spring, stream’. Some instances of   Bovill   may have the same origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Buswell","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Boswell  , of Norman origin."]},{"name":"Bovill","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy whose medieval forms share a similar range of variants, such as Bouville (Seine-Maritime), any of several places called Biéville (Calvados, Manche) or Biville (Manche, Seine-Maritime), Beuzeville-la-Giffard (Seine-Maritime), Boiville (Orne), and perhaps Boudeville (Seine-Maritime). See also   Boswell   and   Beville  ."]},{"name":"Biswell","meanings":["English (Buckinghamshire): possibly from a lost or unidentified place called with Old English <i>bēos</i> ‘coarse grass’ + <i>wella</i> ‘spring, stream’. Alternatively, a variant of   Boswell  ."]},{"name":"Bussell","meanings":["English: variant of   Boswell   (of Norman origin) or   Bissell   1."]},{"name":"Baswell","meanings":["Possibly Scottish: variant of   Boswell  ."]}]},{"name":"Marjory","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual modern spelling of   Margery .  It seems to have arisen as the result of folk etymological association of the name with that of the herb <i>marjoram</i> (  compare  Rosemary  ). This word is of uncertain origin; its Middle English and Old French form was <i>majorane</i>, without the first <i>-r-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Marjory Boswell was born in 1394. She had at least 1 son with Sir Thomas Sibbald of Balgonie - Treasurer of Scotland. She died in Portmoak, Kinross-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1394–":"1394–Surnud","1370–1410":"1370–1410","1430–1450":"1430–1450","1400–1451":"1400–1451","1394–Female":"1394–Surnud","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1451":"1451","1450":"1